==English==

===Etymology===
''a.'' '''1971''', from a riddle: "Where does an 800-pound gorilla sleep?" / "Anywhere it wants."

===Pronunciation===
* {{audio|en|en-au-800-pound gorilla.ogg|Audio (AU)}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|head=800-[[pound]] [[gorilla]]}}

# {{lb|en|idiomatic}} An entity that dominates its environment.
#* {{quote-book|en|title=Data Science at the Command Line|edition=2nd|author=Jeroen Janssens|publisher=O'Reilly|chapter=10|year=2021|isbn=978-1492087915|chapterurl=https://datascienceatthecommandline.com/2e/chapter-10-polyglot-data-science.html|passage=Apache Spark is a cluster-computing framework. It’s the '''800-pound gorilla''' you turn to when it’s impossible to fit your data in memory.}}
# {{lb|en|idiomatic}} Something [[dangerous]], menacing, or frightening that is obvious but not [[address]]ed.
#: {{syn|en|elephant in the room}}

====Usage notes====
* The weight in the metaphor can be varied quantitatively.
* Occasionally other nouns are substituted, most commonly {{m|en|elephant}} from another idiom, but also more context-specific nouns, such as {{m|en|rutabaga}} in an article on gardening.
* Occasionally adjectives are inserted to modify gorilla to bring the metaphor closer to the context.

